                  <provenance>  'Iste est liber R P.' (fol. 121r), and on the back [i.e. spine?] is 'R P'. For the same inscription(s) in Cambridge, Peterhouse, MSS. 107, 135, 160, 238, Cambridge, Gonville and Caius, 94/46, and Oxford, Balliol College, MSS. 147-8, see R. Thomson, <title>A Descriptive Catalogue of the Medieval Manuscripts in the Library of Peterhouse, Cambridge</title> (2016), p. 59 and pl. 31.</provenance>
                  <provenance> A nearly erased inscription on fol. 120 reads 'D ... ... ... de s . . ber ... y . . de seynt Martyn deschaumps' (15th cent.), possibly 'Donum ... Seber presbyteri' of st. Martin in the Fields, London.</provenance><provenance>'Thys bok belongyth to <persName role="fmo" key="person_5157">Robert Blumston prest</persName>' (15th cent.). </provenance><provenance>The name of '<persName role="sgn" key="person_5158">Johannes de Depyng</persName>' occurs on fol. 119v in reversed writing, 14th (?) cent.</provenance><provenance> 'Ex donacione <persName role="fmo" key="person_5159">magistri Johannis Cook de Tekhyll</persName>' 16th cent., cf. 'Johannis Cooke' fol. 2v. (Not in Emden.)
